```

And the HTML structure is:
```html
<div class="group-heading">
  <h2 @text="group.year"></h2>
  <scratch-lines :year="group.year" :count="group.posts.length"></scratch-lines>
</div>
```

The SVG is set to 100% height and width, but it's not stretching to fill the parent container. The issue is likely that the flex container needs `align-items: stretch` to make the SVG child expand vertically, or the `scratch-lines` component itself needs to have `height: 100%` applied to it. In a flex row, items stretch to fill the cross-axis height by default, but for `height: 100%` on the SVG to work, its parent needs an explicit height. The scratch-lines component uses a render template that should output the SVG directly, though WebC might be wrapping it in an additional element that's affecting the height calculation.

Looking at the actual DOM structure, the `<scratch-lines>` element becomes the flex item, not the SVG itself. Since scratch-lines has no explicit height or styling and defaults to `display: inline`, the SVG's `height: 100%` has nothing to reference. I need to either give the scratch-lines element a defined height or make it stretch properly within the flex container. The `<scratch-lines>` wrapper element needs an explicit height or `display: contents` so the SVG's `height: 100%` has something to resolve against and participates properly in the flex layout.

