content.text:
Yeah. The about page uses `.g-main`, so at your FIXME breakpoint (1040px) it's 5 columns, then 6 at 1240px, 10 at 1700px, 11 at 2200px. Since you're hardcoding the breakpoint anyway, you can just inline the number:

```css
@media (min-width: 1040px) {
  ol {
    --offset: calc(var(--g-padding-h) + (100vw - 2 * var(--g-padding-h) - 4 * var(--g-gutter)) / 5 + var(--g-gutter));
    padding-inline-start: var(--offset);
    scroll-padding-inline-start: var(--offset);
  }
}
```

Then update the numbers at the other breakpoints where `--num-cols` changes. Hairy but it tracks the grid exactly.

message.content:
Given this:

--target-cols: 4;
      --p-start: calc(
        var(--g-padding-h) +
          (100vw - 2 * var(--g-padding-h) - 4 * var(--g-gutter)) / 5 +
          var(--g-gutter)
      );

Can you replace the correct places in the formula with the --target-cols var, that way I can just update that in the mqs

content.text:
```css
--target-cols: 4;
--p-start: calc(
  var(--g-padding-h) +
    (100vw - 2 * var(--g-padding-h) - var(--target-cols) * var(--g-gutter)) / (var(--target-cols) + 1) +
    var(--g-gutter)
);
```

The `4` in the gutter count becomes `var(--target-cols)` (number of gutters = num-cols - 1, but since target-cols is already num-cols - 1, it stays as-is). The `5` (total columns) becomes `var(--target-cols) + 1`.

